<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100231577521861></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100231577521861><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100231577521861>RE: Solo tactics</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100231577521861#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=96333><span id=Scholar>JBugman</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>32 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Oct 5th 5:02 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Make sure you have Fireshield on the pet (and you) and pull once with FireBolt.  Wait until the mob almost gets to you and sic the pet.  Wait a little for the pet to fight with the mob (either the pet smacks the mob or the mob smacks the pet and gets Fireshielded), and then nuke the mob once.  Avoid chain nuking the mob until it's at least 50% dead.<br>  If/when you over nuke the mob, take some hits (you're still Fireshielded) and wait for the pet to smack the mob around.  Once the mob reattacks the pet, sit down and wait a bit and renuke.  You'll probably only get agroe'd once; twice and you're nuking waaay too early.<br>  If the mob hits too hard, then heal the pet once (before it gets below 50%) and then renuke.<br><br>  If you pull two or more blues, see how the fight goes and don't be afraid of running like a little girl.  Over nuking two or more mobs and having one aggro you while the other spanks around your pet is an accident (and lost XP) waiting to happen.<br><br>Hope this helps,<br><br>Coddington<br>lvl 27 Mage<br>Terris-Thule<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100198388412767></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100198388412767><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100198388412767>RE: Solo tactics</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100198388412767#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 1st 8:51 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;  Level 31 can be tough trying to solo in the Overthere.  Illomen might be easier and more consistent experience.  If you insist on trying to solo, though, I would suggest learning some basic pet chaining, as well as remembering to fireshield yourself and take some hits for your pet.  Use your level 16 shock of flame to nuke with, so as not to overaggro the mob, and be very selective what you pull.<br><br>    I haven't tried this myself, but you could try this tactic:  Start the fight with your 29 fire pet.  Malise to pull, fireshield yourself.  Sit down as soon as it is safe to do so.  Keep your pet targeted, and when the pet gets below half hps, start casting a new pet, preferrably earth.  Type /pet get lost while casting, then hit Enter once the spell has half a bub left to cast.  The mob will run at you and smack you a little.  Just back off and allow the new pet to engage the mob.  Sit for a sec or two to regain some mana, then stand up and start chain casting shock of flame until the mob is dead.<br><br>    Even at level 30, a mage can still tank a little while soloing.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
